;L=dewey-l&amp;D=1&amp;P=271 Free Speech or Pulp Fictions?]. ''John Dewey Discussion List'' (28 Jan 2003)&lt;/ref>  Rafe Champion war Ã¤hnlich deutlich:  {{Zitat-en|Popperâ€™s ideas have failed to convince the majority of professional philosophers because his theory of conjectural knowledge does not even pretend to provide positively justified foundations of belief. Nobody else does better, but they keep trying, like chemists still in search of the Philosopherâ€™s Stone or physicists trying to build perpetual motion machines.| ref=&lt;ref>Rafe Champion: [http://www.the-rathouse.com/bartagree.html Agreeing to Disagree: Bartleyâ€™s Critique of Reason]. ''Melbourne Age Monthly Review'' (October 1985)&lt;/ref>| Ãœbersetzung=Poppers Ideen konnten die Mehrheit der Berufsphilosophen nicht Ã¼berzeugen, denn seine Theorie des Vermutungswissens versucht gar nicht erst den Eindruck zu erwecken, dass sie positiv gerechtfertigte Grundlagen fÃ¼r GlaubensÃ¼berzeugungen anzubieten hÃ¤tte. Niemand sonst macht es besser, aber sie versuchen es weiter, wie Chemiker, die immer noch nach dem Stein der Weisen suchen oder Physiker, die versuchen, ein [[Perpetuum mobile]] zu bauen.}}  David Miller behauptete zusammenfassend auf dem Popper-Kongress 2007:  {{Zitat-en|What distinguishes science from all other human endeavours is that the accounts of the world that our best, mature sciences deliver are strongly supported by evidence and this evidence gives us the strongest reason to believe them.â€™  That anyway is what is said at the beginning of the advertisement for a recent conference on induction at a celebrated seat of learning in the UK. It shows how much critical rationalists still have to do to make known the message of ''Logik der Forschung'' concerning what empirical evidence is able to do and what it does [â€¦] [critical rationalists] are rightly proud of having the only house in the neighbourhood that is logically watertight [although] we must inevitably be aware that not everythin